Your question:

If refresh token is stored in HttpOnly + SameSite=Strict + Secure cookie, and that protects from CSRF… then why not store access token the same way?

Very smart question. Let’s go step by step.

🧠 First Important Clarification

SameSite=Strict does NOT eliminate all CSRF risk.

It reduces it.

There are edge cases:

SameSite=Lax allows some top-level navigation

Older browsers may not enforce correctly

Misconfiguration is common

Subdomain attacks possible

CORS misconfigurations happen

Security engineers avoid relying on a single mechanism.

🚨 But The Bigger Reason Is Architectural

The real reason is this:

👉 Access token is meant for API authorization
👉 Refresh token is meant for session renewal

They serve different purposes.

🟢 Why Access Token in Header Is Cleaner

When access token is sent in:

Authorization: Bearer <token>

It gives:

Explicit authentication

Clear API design

Stateless REST behavior

No automatic browser behavior

Works perfectly for mobile apps

Works for third-party API consumers

Cookies are browser-specific.

Authorization header works everywhere.

That’s important.

🟡 What Happens If You Put Access Token in Cookie?

Then your API becomes:

Browser-dependent

Cookie-dependent

Closer to session-based auth

Less flexible for mobile apps / external clients

You lose one big advantage of JWT: clean API auth via header.

🔐 Now Let’s Talk Pure Security

Even with:

HttpOnly
Secure
SameSite=Strict

If access token is in cookie:

It is automatically attached to ALL requests

Including unintended ones

You must still implement CSRF protection

Now your system needs:

CSRF tokens

Double submit pattern

Strict CORS

Careful SameSite config

Complexity increases.

🎯 Why Split Tokens Instead?

Modern SPA architecture says:

👉 Keep authentication explicit
👉 Keep long-lived credential protected

So:

Token	Storage	Why
Access	Memory	Explicit auth header, no auto-send
Refresh	HttpOnly cookie	Protected from JS

This minimizes attack surface.

🧠 Another Very Important Concept

Access token is short-lived (10–15 minutes).

Even if stolen:

Limited damage.

Refresh token is long-lived (7–30 days).

If stolen:

Massive damage.

So we protect the long-lived credential more strictly.

That’s the core design philosophy.

🧩 Real-World Reality

Some companies DO store access token in HttpOnly cookie.

But when they do, they:

Implement CSRF tokens

Treat it like session-based auth

Accept the complexity

It’s not wrong.

It’s a tradeoff.

🎯 Interview-Level Balanced Answer

If interviewer pushes:

Why not store access token also in HttpOnly cookie?

You answer:

While it's technically possible, storing access tokens in cookies makes them automatically attached to every request, increasing CSRF complexity and coupling authentication to browser behavior. Using Authorization headers keeps authentication explicit and works consistently across web, mobile, and third-party clients. Therefore, modern SPA architectures typically store short-lived access tokens in memory and long-lived refresh tokens in HttpOnly cookies.

That sounds mature and balanced.

